00:22:36.490 --> 00:22:37.630
I'll start with the bad,

00:22:37.630 --> 00:22:39.140
we'll move on to the appalling,

00:22:39.140 --> 00:22:40.870
and we'll finish with the
catastrophic.

00:22:41.460 --> 00:22:42.550
Let's go back to the term

00:22:42.550 --> 00:22:43.440
'sound mind'.

00:22:43.780 --> 00:22:45.060
When treating a patient who says

00:22:45.060 --> 00:22:46.650
they've considered ending their life,

00:22:46.650 --> 00:22:49.120
a mental health professional
will seek to determine

00:22:49.120 --> 00:22:50.830
whether or not the
patient is experiencing

00:22:50.830 --> 00:22:52.300
a mental health crisis,

00:22:52.300 --> 00:22:53.470
which is a state of mind

00:22:53.470 --> 00:22:55.800
distinctly different to
the norm for that person.

00:22:56.170 --> 00:22:58.580
There's a massively heightened
danger of self-harm

00:22:58.580 --> 00:23:00.120
during a mental health crisis,

00:23:00.120 --> 00:23:01.960
because to the person
experiencing it,

00:23:01.960 --> 00:23:02.810
the future

00:23:02.810 --> 00:23:04.640
or any possibility of a future

00:23:04.640 --> 00:23:05.860
can get really obscured.

00:23:06.150 --> 00:23:08.510
Life can seem like a
moment-to-moment existence,

00:23:08.510 --> 00:23:10.250
and recovery can seem impossible.

00:23:10.540 --> 00:23:12.100
As Professor Rory O’Connor,

00:23:12.100 --> 00:23:14.430
who leads the S---cidal Behaviour
Research Laboratory

00:23:14.430 --> 00:23:16.420
at the University
of Glasgow, puts it:

00:23:16.420 --> 00:23:17.850
"People... take their own lives"

00:23:17.850 --> 00:23:19.840
"when they can see
no end to their pain,"

00:23:19.840 --> 00:23:21.150
"when they feel trapped by it"

00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:22.320
"and that there is no way out."

00:23:22.730 --> 00:23:23.730
"Like physical pain,"

00:23:23.730 --> 00:23:26.240
"there is only so much mental
pain that we can withstand"

00:23:26.240 --> 00:23:27.620
"and, when we reach our limit,"

00:23:27.620 --> 00:23:28.600
"something has to give."

00:23:28.910 --> 00:23:30.410
"Sadly, for too many people,"

00:23:30.410 --> 00:23:31.780
"it is life that gives."

00:23:31.780 --> 00:23:32.550
The thing is,

00:23:32.550 --> 00:23:34.450
once a mental health crisis is over,

00:23:34.450 --> 00:23:36.680
this view is nowhere near
as black and white.

00:23:36.970 --> 00:23:39.610
To quote a representative at
the Samaritans that I spoke to:

00:23:39.610 --> 00:23:42.050
"A mental health crisis
can feel very intense,"

00:23:42.050 --> 00:23:43.640
"but these feelings are treatable,"

00:23:43.640 --> 00:23:44.580
"things change,"

00:23:44.580 --> 00:23:45.730
"the feelings pass,"

00:23:45.730 --> 00:23:46.730
"things can get better."

00:23:47.110 --> 00:23:49.000
To quote Professor
Rory O’Connor again:

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:51.770
"For most people, s---icide
risk is usually short-term"

00:23:51.770 --> 00:23:53.600
"and linked to a specific situation,"

00:23:53.600 --> 00:23:55.400
"often an interpersonal crisis."

00:23:55.680 --> 00:23:58.470
"While s---cidal thoughts may
come back again for some people,"

00:23:58.470 --> 00:24:00.650
"the vast majority will
make a full recovery."

00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:01.630
So,

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:03.870
given the nature of a
mental health crisis,

00:24:03.870 --> 00:24:06.370
where the ability to act
in one’s own self interest

00:24:06.370 --> 00:24:08.190
can be temporarily impaired,

00:24:08.190 --> 00:24:11.580
